{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:52:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:52:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.37,0.31,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5231"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of worsening lethargy, shortness of breath and dizziness. She reports having black-coloured stools two days ago. She has a medical history of ulcerative colitis and atrial fibrillation. Three weeks ago, she was commenced on a short course of prednisolone following an ulcerative colitis flare-up. Her regular medications include apixaban.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 95/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Digital rectal examination reveals melaena. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 66 g/L (120-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 7.3 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 345 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrea: 14.1 mmol/L (2.8-7.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine: 95 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFerritin: 3 \u00b5g/L (30-310)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETransferrin: 3.2 g/L (2.0-3.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is given intravenous resuscitation with normal saline initially. A group and match is ordered and two units of blood are then given. With this fluid replacement, her blood pressure improves to 110/70 mmHg and pulse settles to 100/min. A venous blood gas shows her haemoglobin has improved to 85 g/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iron infusion","Gastroscopy","Flexible sigmoidoscopy","Observe and monitor the patient","Capsule endoscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms indicative of an upper gastrointestinal (UGI) bleed, likely exacerbated by her recent course of prednisolone and ongoing anticoagulation with apixaban. After initial resuscitation and haemodynamic stabilization, which has been achieved in this case, the priority is to identify and control the source of bleeding. The most appropriate next step in management is therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows direct visualization of the upper GI tract, identification of the bleeding source, and potential therapeutic intervention such as clipping, cauterization, or injection of adrenaline to stop active bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron infusion\u003C/strong\u003E, while eventually necessary to treat this patient\u0027s iron deficiency anaemia, is not the immediate priority. The focus should be on identifying and controlling the source of active bleeding before addressing the chronic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate for investigating lower GI bleeding or a flare of ulcerative colitis. Although the patient\u0027s ulcerative colitis may lead to lower gastrointestinal bleeding, given the presence of melaena and the high urea level suggests an upper GI source of bleeding, and an upper endoscopy is more appropriate at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserve and monitor the patient\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step. While the patient has shown some improvement with initial resuscitation, the underlying cause of bleeding needs to be identified and addressed to prevent further deterioration. Her significant anaemia, haemodynamic instability, and ongoing melaena at presentation are all indicators for the need for more prompt intervention. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECapsule endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used to investigate obscure GI bleeding when upper endoscopy and colonoscopy have been inconclusive. It is not the first-line investigation for suspected acute upper GI bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The priority in management of severe upper gastrointestinal bleeding is to resuscitate the patient, ensure haemodynamic stability and then identify and control the source of bleeding.","Steroids and anticoagulants increase the risk of upper gastrointestinal bleeding."],"references":["Narum S, Westergren T, Klemp M. Corticosteroids and risk of gastrointestinal bleeding: A systematic review and meta-analysis. BMJ Open. 2014;4(5).","Laine L, Barkun AN, Saltzman JR, Martel M, Leontiadis GI. ACG clinical guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal and ulcer bleeding. American Journal of Gastroenterology. 2021;116(5):899\u2013917."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41250"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T15:32:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T15:32:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5231"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66